1
00:00:00,000 --> 00:00:03,496
Every time a new AI model launches, there is a number.

2
00:00:03,496 --> 00:00:04,768
Ninety-two percent on this.

3
00:00:04,768 --> 00:00:06,039
Eighty-eight percent on that.

4
00:00:06,039 --> 00:00:08,900
State of the art on something with an acronym.

5
00:00:08,900 --> 00:00:11,126
The number is supposed to tell you

6
00:00:11,126 --> 00:00:13,351
how good the model is — and

7
00:00:13,351 --> 00:00:15,576
most of the work that produced it

8
00:00:15,576 --> 00:00:17,483
never makes it into the headline.

9
00:00:17,483 --> 00:00:19,391
This video is a small toolkit.

10
00:00:19,391 --> 00:00:21,934
Six places a benchmark score can mislead you,

11
00:00:21,934 --> 00:00:24,159
and seven questions you can ask the

12
00:00:24,159 --> 00:00:25,748
next time you see one.

13
00:00:25,748 --> 00:00:27,974
Not as a debunking — benchmarks are

14
00:00:27,974 --> 00:00:30,199
often the best thing we have —

15
00:00:30,199 --> 00:00:33,695
but so you can decide for yourself how impressed to be.

16
00:00:33,695 --> 00:00:36,448
A benchmark, stripped down, is three things.

17
00:00:36,448 --> 00:00:39,200
A fixed test set: a list of

18
00:00:39,199 --> 00:00:41,558
questions or tasks someone wrote down.

19
00:00:41,558 --> 00:00:44,310
Take MMLU, which you have probably seen

20
00:00:44,310 --> 00:00:47,849
quoted — fifty-seven subjects, around fourteen thousand multiple-choice questions,

21
00:00:47,849 --> 00:00:50,207
from elementary math to professional law.

22
00:00:50,207 --> 00:00:52,173
That is the test set.

23
00:00:52,173 --> 00:00:54,925
The second thing is a prompt format:

24
00:00:54,925 --> 00:00:57,677
how you hand each question to the

25
00:00:57,677 --> 00:01:00,429
model — the wording, the system message,

26
00:01:00,429 --> 00:01:02,788
whether you give worked examples first,

27
00:01:02,788 --> 00:01:05,540
whether you let it think out loud.

28
00:01:05,540 --> 00:01:08,292
And the third is a scoring rule:

29
00:01:08,292 --> 00:01:11,437
how you turn the answer into a number.

30
00:01:11,437 --> 00:01:15,762
Change any one of those, and you get a different score.

31
00:01:15,762 --> 00:01:18,121
Same model, same questions, different number.

32
00:01:18,121 --> 00:01:20,873
Most arguments about benchmarks are really arguments

33
00:01:20,873 --> 00:01:23,231
about one of these three boxes.

34
00:01:23,231 --> 00:01:24,746
Trap one is contamination.

35
00:01:24,746 --> 00:01:28,910
Modern models are trained on a huge slice of the internet.

36
00:01:28,910 --> 00:01:32,316
Many benchmarks have been on the internet for years.

37
00:01:32,316 --> 00:01:34,966
So sometimes a model isn't solving a

38
00:01:34,966 --> 00:01:36,859
question — it's recognizing it.

39
00:01:36,859 --> 00:01:38,751
Honest evaluations defend against this.

40
00:01:38,751 --> 00:01:41,401
They hold out test sets the model

41
00:01:41,401 --> 00:01:43,294
was not allowed to see.

42
00:01:43,294 --> 00:01:46,322
They run decontamination checks against the training data.

43
00:01:46,322 --> 00:01:49,729
Some benchmarks, like BIG-bench, embed unique strings called canaries,

44
00:01:49,729 --> 00:01:52,379
so labs can scan their training data

45
00:01:52,379 --> 00:01:55,029
and see if any questions leaked in.

46
00:01:55,029 --> 00:01:57,678
What to look for: was the test

47
00:01:57,678 --> 00:02:00,328
set published after the model's training cutoff,

48
00:02:00,328 --> 00:02:03,356
and did the lab run a contamination check.

49
00:02:03,356 --> 00:02:06,006
If both answers are "I don't know,"

50
00:02:06,006 --> 00:02:09,792
your prior on the score should be a little weaker.

51
00:02:09,792 --> 00:02:11,823
Trap two is the ceiling.

52
00:02:11,823 --> 00:02:14,668
The first generation of a benchmark might

53
00:02:14,668 --> 00:02:17,513
land models in the sixties or seventies.

54
00:02:17,513 --> 00:02:21,577
A few years later, every frontier model scores above ninety.

55
00:02:21,577 --> 00:02:24,421
At that point the benchmark isn't really

56
00:02:24,421 --> 00:02:27,266
measuring capability anymore — it's measuring whichever

57
00:02:27,266 --> 00:02:30,924
last few percent of questions happen to be ambiguous,

58
00:02:30,924 --> 00:02:33,768
badly worded, or have wrong answer keys.

59
00:02:33,768 --> 00:02:37,832
The difference between ninety-four and ninety-five might just be noise.

60
00:02:37,832 --> 00:02:40,270
Near-saturated benchmarks are popular in announcements,

61
00:02:40,270 --> 00:02:43,115
because every gain looks dramatic on a

62
00:02:43,115 --> 00:02:45,960
chart that ends close to a hundred.

63
00:02:45,960 --> 00:02:48,805
What to look for: where is this

64
00:02:48,805 --> 00:02:50,837
benchmark on its progress curve.

65
00:02:50,837 --> 00:02:53,681
If everyone is already near the top,

66
00:02:53,681 --> 00:02:58,151
the headline number is closer to a tiebreaker than a measurement.

67
00:02:58,151 --> 00:03:01,340
Trap three is hiding inside the word "average".

68
00:03:01,340 --> 00:03:04,130
A score like ninety-two on a multi-subject

69
00:03:04,130 --> 00:03:07,717
benchmark is a number for an imaginary average user.

70
00:03:07,717 --> 00:03:10,507
A real user has a specific question.

71
00:03:10,507 --> 00:03:14,493
A model that's ninety-two overall can be ninety-nine on ethics,

72
00:03:14,493 --> 00:03:17,283
ninety-six on history, and seventy-eight on physics

73
00:03:17,283 --> 00:03:20,073
— and if you came for physics,

74
00:03:20,073 --> 00:03:24,059
that overall number was the wrong number for your task.

75
00:03:24,059 --> 00:03:27,646
The fix is almost always to find the subscores.

76
00:03:27,646 --> 00:03:30,835
Most reputable benchmarks publish them; many summaries don't.

77
00:03:30,835 --> 00:03:34,024
What to look for: a breakdown by category,

78
00:03:34,024 --> 00:03:36,017
and especially the worst category.

79
00:03:36,017 --> 00:03:38,807
The shape of the score is often

80
00:03:38,807 --> 00:03:40,799
more informative than its mean.

81
00:03:40,799 --> 00:03:44,699
Trap four is the gap between the benchmark and the task.

82
00:03:44,699 --> 00:03:48,243
The same question can be asked as a multiple-choice problem,

83
00:03:48,243 --> 00:03:50,724
as a free-response question, or as a

84
00:03:50,724 --> 00:03:53,206
tool-use task — and the same model

85
00:03:53,206 --> 00:03:56,041
will give you noticeably different scores on each.

86
00:03:56,041 --> 00:03:58,523
Small changes to the prompt — how

87
00:03:58,523 --> 00:04:01,358
many examples you give, whether you allow chain-of-thought,

88
00:04:01,358 --> 00:04:03,839
even the exact wording of the instruction

89
00:04:03,839 --> 00:04:07,739
— can move scores by several points, and sometimes much more.

90
00:04:07,739 --> 00:04:10,220
So when you see "Model X gets

91
00:04:10,220 --> 00:04:12,701
eighty-nine on Benchmark Y," what you're really

92
00:04:12,701 --> 00:04:15,182
seeing is "Model X gets eighty-nine on

93
00:04:15,182 --> 00:04:17,663
Benchmark Y when prompted in this specific

94
00:04:17,663 --> 00:04:19,790
way." If the prompt isn't published,

95
00:04:19,790 --> 00:04:22,271
you don't really know what you're comparing.

96
00:04:22,271 --> 00:04:23,662
Trap five is grading.

97
00:04:23,662 --> 00:04:25,747
For multiple-choice tests this is easy.

98
00:04:25,747 --> 00:04:27,832
For free-response, code, or open-ended writing,

99
00:04:27,832 --> 00:04:30,959
somebody has to decide whether the answer is good.

100
00:04:30,959 --> 00:04:32,349
Sometimes it's a human.

101
00:04:32,349 --> 00:04:33,739
Sometimes it's another model.

102
00:04:33,739 --> 00:04:36,172
If the grader is itself an AI,

103
00:04:36,172 --> 00:04:37,909
it has its own preferences,

104
00:04:37,909 --> 00:04:40,342
and those preferences leak into the score.

105
00:04:40,342 --> 00:04:42,774
In an earlier video on this channel

106
00:04:42,774 --> 00:04:45,207
I went through an experiment where flipping

107
00:04:45,207 --> 00:04:47,639
just the author label on an essay

108
00:04:47,639 --> 00:04:50,072
changed the grade by about a third

109
00:04:50,072 --> 00:04:52,505
of a point on a ten-point scale

110
00:04:52,505 --> 00:04:54,242
— for the same essay.

111
00:04:54,242 --> 00:04:56,675
So when a model is the judge,

112
00:04:56,675 --> 00:04:59,107
"how good is this answer" becomes partly

113
00:04:59,107 --> 00:05:01,540
"how much does the judge like this

114
00:05:01,540 --> 00:05:03,972
kind of answer." What to look for:

115
00:05:03,972 --> 00:05:05,710
is the grader a model,

116
00:05:05,710 --> 00:05:08,142
a human pool, or a strict rubric.

117
00:05:08,142 --> 00:05:09,880
And if it's a model,

118
00:05:09,880 --> 00:05:13,007
what is its relationship to the model being graded.

119
00:05:13,007 --> 00:05:15,520
Trap six is the number of attempts.

120
00:05:15,520 --> 00:05:18,032
A benchmark score in a launch post

121
00:05:18,032 --> 00:05:19,827
is often a single run.

122
00:05:19,827 --> 00:05:22,340
Run the same model on the same

123
00:05:22,340 --> 00:05:24,134
benchmark with different random seeds,

124
00:05:24,134 --> 00:05:26,647
and the score wobbles, typically by one

125
00:05:26,647 --> 00:05:29,159
to a few points just from sampling.

126
00:05:29,159 --> 00:05:32,749
Sometimes the reported number is the best of several runs,

127
00:05:32,749 --> 00:05:35,261
or the result with the most favorable

128
00:05:35,261 --> 00:05:37,056
prompt out of many tried.

129
00:05:37,056 --> 00:05:39,568
That doesn't mean the result is fake.

130
00:05:39,568 --> 00:05:42,081
It does mean the headline number is

131
00:05:42,081 --> 00:05:44,952
closer to a maximum than to a mean.

132
00:05:44,952 --> 00:05:47,106
What to look for: confidence intervals,

133
00:05:47,106 --> 00:05:49,618
the number of runs, and whether the

134
00:05:49,618 --> 00:05:53,207
lab published the worst run, not only the best one.

135
00:05:53,207 --> 00:05:54,371
That's six traps.

136
00:05:54,371 --> 00:05:57,087
Here they are as seven questions you

137
00:05:57,087 --> 00:05:59,026
can keep in your head.

138
00:05:59,026 --> 00:06:00,966
What's in the test set,

139
00:06:00,966 --> 00:06:03,681
and could the model have seen it.

140
00:06:03,681 --> 00:06:05,621
Is the benchmark near saturation.

141
00:06:05,621 --> 00:06:07,560
Is there a subscore breakdown.

142
00:06:07,560 --> 00:06:10,276
What prompt format, and how many examples.

143
00:06:10,276 --> 00:06:12,603
Who or what graded the answers.

144
00:06:12,603 --> 00:06:16,095
How many runs, and how much do they vary.

145
00:06:16,095 --> 00:06:18,810
And the question that quietly matters most:

146
00:06:18,810 --> 00:06:21,138
what does this benchmark not measure.

147
00:06:21,138 --> 00:06:23,077
Most benchmarks measure something narrow.

148
00:06:23,077 --> 00:06:26,956
Many of the things we care about — long-horizon reasoning,

149
00:06:26,956 --> 00:06:31,223
real-world reliability, behavior under pressure — are still hard to test.

150
00:06:31,223 --> 00:06:33,817
The goal here is not to make

151
00:06:33,817 --> 00:06:36,040
you distrust every number you see.

152
00:06:36,040 --> 00:06:37,151
Benchmarks are useful.

153
00:06:37,151 --> 00:06:38,634
Many are carefully built.

154
00:06:38,634 --> 00:06:41,598
Some labs report them in detail and honestly.

155
00:06:41,598 --> 00:06:44,191
The goal is to put the number

156
00:06:44,191 --> 00:06:46,784
in context — to remember that a

157
00:06:46,784 --> 00:06:49,748
score is a measurement, and measurements have setups,

158
00:06:49,748 --> 00:06:53,083
and setups make choices, and choices change the answer.

159
00:06:53,083 --> 00:06:55,306
Once you can see those choices,

160
00:06:55,306 --> 00:06:58,270
the story behind a headline gets more interesting,

161
00:06:58,270 --> 00:06:59,752
and usually more accurate.

162
00:06:59,752 --> 00:07:02,346
Description has links to the benchmarks I

163
00:07:02,346 --> 00:07:05,680
mentioned and to the prior research on grader effects.

164
00:07:05,680 --> 00:07:06,791
Thanks for watching.
